.TH "ATOMIC\-UPGRADE" "8" "" "atomic\-upgrade" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
atomic\-upgrade \[em] atomic system upgrades for Arch Linux on Btrfs
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]atomic\-upgrade\f[R] [\f[B]\-n\f[R]|\f[B]\-\-dry\-run\f[R]]
[\f[B]\-t\f[R]|\f[B]\-\-tag\f[R] \f[I]TAG\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-no\-gc\f[R]]
[\f[B]\-\-separate\-home\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-copy\-files\f[R] \f[I]\[lq]FILE
\&...\[rq]\f[R]] [\f[B]\-\-\f[R] \f[I]COMMAND\f[R]\&...]
.PP
\f[B]atomic\-rebuild\-uki\f[R] [\f[B]\-l\f[R]|\f[B]\-\-list\f[R]]
\f[I]GEN_ID\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]atomic\-upgrade\f[R] creates a Btrfs snapshot of the current root
subvolume, mounts it, runs a command inside a chroot (default:
\f[B]pacman \-Syu\f[R]), updates \f[I]fstab\f[R], builds a Unified
Kernel Image (UKI), optionally signs it with \f[B]sbctl\f[R](8), and
runs garbage collection.
.PP
Each generation is a snapshot + UKI pair.
The UKI contains the kernel and initramfs from that snapshot, and its
cmdline points to that specific subvolume.
Rollback works because each boot menu entry maps to one complete system
state.
.PP
The new generation becomes active on next reboot.
Rollback is performed by selecting a previous UKI entry in the boot
menu.
Any bootloader or UEFI firmware that discovers Type #2 entries works
\[em] systemd\-boot, rEFInd, direct UEFI boot, etc.
.PP
\f[B]atomic\-rebuild\-uki\f[R] rebuilds the UKI for an existing
generation subvolume.
Use it to recover an accidentally deleted \f[I].efi\f[R] file.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-n\f[R], \f[B]\-\-dry\-run\f[R]
Show what would be done without making changes.
For the default \f[B]pacman \-Syu\f[R] command, also prints available
upgrades.
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R], \f[B]\-\-tag\f[R] \f[I]TAG\f[R]
Append \f[I]TAG\f[R] to the generation timestamp.
Only letters, numbers, hyphens, and underscores are allowed (max 48
characters).
Example: \f[B]\-t pre\-nvidia\f[R] creates
\f[I]root\-20260317\-213728\-pre\-nvidia\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-\-no\-gc\f[R]
Skip garbage collection after a successful upgrade.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-separate\-home\f[R]
Create an isolated \f[I]/home\f[R] Btrfs subvolume for this generation.
The subvolume is named \f[I]home\-TAG\f[R], so \f[B]\-\-tag\f[R] is
required.
If a subvolume with that name already exists, it is reused.
See \f[B]HOME ISOLATION\f[R] below.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-copy\-files\f[R] \f[I]\[lq]FILE \&...\[rq]\f[R]
Space\-separated list of files to copy from the current
\f[I]/home//\f[R] into the new home subvolume.
Paths are relative to the user\[cq]s home directory.
Requires \f[B]\-\-separate\-home\f[R].
Overrides \f[B]HOME_COPY_FILES\f[R] from \f[B]atomic.conf\f[R](5).
Paths with spaces are not supported.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-\f[R] \f[I]COMMAND\f[R]\&...
Run \f[I]COMMAND\f[R] in the snapshot chroot instead of the default
\f[B]pacman \-Syu\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\-\-help\f[R]
Show usage summary and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\-V\f[R], \f[B]\-\-version\f[R]
Show version and exit.
.SH HOME ISOLATION
\f[B]This feature is for throwaway experiments, not permanent
environments.\f[R] Permanent setups should use regular generations with
the shared \f[I]/home\f[R] subvolume.
.PP
When \f[B]\-\-separate\-home\f[R] is used, the generation gets its own
\f[I]/home\f[R] subvolume so that experiments with dotfiles, desktop
environment configs, or user\-level packages do not affect the main
home.
If the experiment fails, delete the generation; garbage collection will
report the orphan home subvolume but will \f[B]never auto\-delete
it\f[R] (it may contain user data).
.PP
The home subvolume is populated with empty user directories (matching
users with UID >= 1000) and, optionally, specific files copied from the
current home via \f[B]\-\-copy\-files\f[R] or the
\f[B]HOME_COPY_FILES\f[R] config option.
.PP
Safety: absolute paths and \f[B]..\f[R] traversal in file lists are
rejected.
.SH UPGRADE GUARD
Two guard layers prevent accidental direct system upgrades, controlled
by the \f[B]UPGRADE_GUARD\f[R] option in \f[B]atomic.conf\f[R](5)
(enabled by default).
.TP
\f[B]Pacman hook\f[R] (\f[B]atomic\-guard\f[R])
A pre\-transaction hook that blocks \f[B]pacman \-Syu\f[R] unless called
from \f[B]atomic\-upgrade\f[R] (verified via environment variable and
file lock) or from an AUR helper (\f[B]yay\f[R], \f[B]paru\f[R],
\f[B]pikaur\f[R], \f[B]aura\f[R]).
Package installs, removals, and queries are never blocked.
.TP
\f[B]Pacman wrapper\f[R] (\f[I]/usr/local/bin/pacman\f[R])
Intercepts \f[B]pacman \-Syu\f[R] and prompts the user to use
\f[B]atomic\-upgrade\f[R] instead.
In non\-interactive contexts (piped stdin), it aborts for safety.
Also warns when \f[B]\-Sy\f[R] is used without \f[B]\-u\f[R] (partial
upgrade risk).
.PP
Both layers read \f[B]UPGRADE_GUARD\f[R] at runtime \[em] changing the
value in \f[B]atomic.conf\f[R](5) takes effect immediately.
.PP
When an AUR helper is detected in the process tree, the hook allows the
transaction but prints a warning that the upgrade runs on the live
system and is not atomic.
.SH DISK SPACE CHECKS
Before creating a snapshot, the following checks are performed:
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]Btrfs\f[R]: the operation is blocked only when free space is below
the percentage threshold (default 10%) \f[B]and\f[R] below 2 GB
absolute.
On large disks with low percentage but sufficient absolute free space, a
warning is shown and the operation proceeds.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]ESP\f[R]: requires at least 250 MB free.
.PP
If space cannot be determined, a warning is shown and the operation
proceeds.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Success.
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Error.
Common causes: missing dependencies, insufficient disk space, lock held
by another instance, chroot command failure, UKI build failure, fstab
update failure.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]ATOMIC_UPGRADE\f[R]
Set to \f[B]1\f[R] by \f[B]atomic\-upgrade\f[R] before invoking pacman.
Used by \f[B]atomic\-guard\f[R] to verify the caller.
Should not be set manually.
.TP
\f[B]CONFIG_FILE\f[R]
Override path to the configuration file (default:
\f[I]/etc/atomic.conf\f[R]).
Intended for testing.
.TP
\f[B]LOCK_FILE\f[R]
Override path to the lock file (default:
\f[I]/run/atomic/atomic\-upgrade.lock\f[R]).
Intended for testing.
.SH FILES
.TP
\f[I]/etc/atomic.conf\f[R]
Configuration file.
See \f[B]atomic.conf\f[R](5).
.TP
\f[I]/usr/lib/atomic/common.sh\f[R]
Shared shell library.
.TP
\f[I]/usr/lib/atomic/config.py\f[R]
Config file parser with proper quote handling via \f[CR]shlex\f[R].
.TP
\f[I]/usr/lib/atomic/fstab.py\f[R]
Safe fstab manipulation (atomic write, verification, rollback).
.TP
\f[I]/usr/lib/atomic/rootdev.py\f[R]
Root device auto\-detection and kernel cmdline generation.
.TP
\f[I]/run/atomic/atomic\-upgrade.lock\f[R]
Exclusive lock file preventing concurrent operations.
.TP
\f[I]/efi/EFI/Linux/arch\-*.efi\f[R]
Unified Kernel Images, one per generation.
.SH EXAMPLES
Standard system upgrade:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade
.EE
.PP
Preview without changes:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-\-dry\-run
.EE
.PP
Install a specific package atomically:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-\- pacman \-S nvidia\-dkms
.EE
.PP
Run AUR helper inside the snapshot:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-\- sudo \-u myuser yay \-Syu
.EE
.PP
Upgrade with a custom tag:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-t pre\-nvidia
.EE
.PP
Experiment with KDE in isolated home (throwaway):
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-\-separate\-home \-t kde \-\- pacman \-S plasma\-meta
.EE
.PP
Experiment with dev tools, copying dotfiles:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-upgrade \-\-separate\-home \-t dev \-\-copy\-files \[dq].bashrc .ssh\[dq] \-\- pacman \-S base\-devel
.EE
.PP
Rebuild a missing UKI:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-rebuild\-uki 20250208\-134725
.EE
.PP
List subvolumes and UKI status:
.IP
.EX
sudo atomic\-rebuild\-uki \-\-list
.EE
